article.description: Kayla Tetschlag and Kati Harty scored 12 points apiece on Sunday to lead the University of Wisconsin-Green Bay to a 65-41 win over UW-Milwaukee and a berth in the NCAA tournament as the Horizon League Tournament champions.
article.headline: Tetschlag, Harty lead UW-Green Bay to Horizon title
article.linkText: UW-Green Bay routs UW-Milwaukee to earn bid
article.story:
GREEN BAY, Wis. -- University of Wisconsin-Green Bay coach Matt Bollant and senior guard Kati Harty ended the Horizon League tournament with a victory lap as they slapped hands with home fans.

Green Bay finished its perfect run through the conference Sunday, beating UW-Milwaukee 65-41 in the tournament championship game for an automatic NCAA bid.

Last year, Green Bay was stunned at home in the semifinals and was left out of the NCAA tournament -- despite going 26-6 overall and 17-1 in the league.

"It was a healthy [nervousness]," Bollant said. "It wasn't a fear like, 'Oh, my gosh, could we lose again?' It was more of a confident, 'We've done the right things, and good things are going to happen because of it.' "

Kayla Tetschlag and Harty scored 12 points apiece to lead Green Bay to the win. Harty was named the tournament's outstanding player. Lavesa Glover and Celeste Hoewisch added nine each for the Phoenix.

Green Bay (29-3) went 18-0 in the Horizon League's regular season, ran its winning streak to 21 games and will make its ninth NCAA appearance since the 1994-95 season.

"This is one of the best Green Bay teams that they've put together," Milwaukee coach Sandy Botham said. "They earned this victory. No ifs, ands or buts about it, and they're going to be a great representative in the NCAA tournament for the Horizon League."

The Phoenix were leading 18-14 when they went on a 14-2 run over the final six minutes of the first half to take control. The Phoenix, who entered the game leading the nation in scoring defense, led 32-16 at halftime.

Milwaukee (15-18) hit 50 percent of its shots, but had more turnovers (20) than field-goal attempts (14).

Green Bay's defense was at its best against Milwaukee's top player. Traci Edwards, the state's all-time scoring leader, was shut out in the first half and barely touched the ball in scoring position. The 6-foot-2 senior, the conference's co-player of the year, was held to just one shot despite playing all 20 minutes.

Edwards, who finally scored in the lane with 15:25 remaining, ended with 11 points.

"It's ball pressure. They come up on you hard. If you're not ready for it, you're going to turn it over," Edwards said.

Botham said she saw a "killer instinct" in the Phoenix and a determination to not let last year's tournament misstep ruin this season.

"There's no words for it," Glover said. "You just want to go out there and scream and be happy."
